  "texts": [
    "Computing the idempotents of the rational Goodwillie-Burnside ring then amounts to inverting this matrix (Theorem 2.6).",
    "In particular, for each 1 ≤ 𝑖 ≤ 𝑑 we obtain an idempotent 𝑒 𝑖 of the Goodwillie-Burnside ring 𝐴 Q (𝑑), corresponding to the projection on the 𝑖-th factor in the product 1≤𝑖≤𝑑 Q.By work of Arone, Barthel, Heard and Sanders [ABHS25], the Goodwillie-Burnside ring is the endomorphism ring of the unit of the homotopy category of 𝑑-excisive functors (Theorem 5.1), and hence these idempotents lift to the category of rational excisive functors, and induce a splitting of the category of rational excisive functors into an 𝑒 𝑑 -local piece and its orthogonal complement a (1 -𝑒 𝑑)-local piece.The final step in the proof is to identify the orthogonal pieces in the splitting.",
    "To do this, we compute the kernel of the natural map 𝐴 Q (𝑑) → 𝐴 Q (𝑑 -1) coming from the inclusion of a subcategory Epi ≤𝑑-1 into Epi ≤𝑑, showing that it is generated by the top idempotent 𝑒 𝑑 (Theorem 3.6).",
    "This map on rational Goodwillie-Burnside rings corresponds to the universal map 𝑃 𝑑 𝐹 → 𝑃 𝑑-1 𝐹 (Theorem 5.2).",
    "It follows that for 𝐹: Sp → Sp a rational 𝑑-excisive functor, peeling off the top idempotent splits the Goodwillie tower of 𝐹 into two pieces,𝑒 𝑑 -local (1 -𝑒 𝑑)-local 𝐹 𝑃 𝑑-1 𝐹 • • • 𝑃 1 𝐹 𝐷 𝑑 𝐹 𝐷 𝑑-1 𝐹 𝐷 1 𝐹 the third author was supported by the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council under grant number EP/Z534705/1. 2."
